### CSS Combinators

**Combinators** explain the relationship between two selectors.

---

### Types of Combinators

| Combinator | Symbol | Example | Selects |
|-----------|--------|---------|---------|
| Descendant | space | `div p` | All `<p>` inside `<div>` |
| Child | `>` | `div > p` | Direct children only |
| Adjacent sibling | `+` | `h2 + p` | First `<p>` after `<h2>` |
| General sibling | `~` | `h2 ~ p` | All `<p>` after `<h2>` |

---

### Descendant Selector (Space)

```css
/* All paragraphs inside any div */
div p {
  color: blue;
}
```

Targets **all** nested levels.

---

### Child Selector (`>`)

```css
/* Direct children only (not nested deeper) */
div > p {
  color: green;
}
```

---

### Adjacent Sibling (`+`)

```css
/* First p immediately after h2 */
h2 + p {
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

---

### General Sibling (`~`)

```css
/* All p elements after h2 (same parent) */
h2 ~ p {
  color: gray;
}
```

---

> **Key Point:** Combinators chain relationships. `div > p` is more specific than `div p`. Use child selector when you want only direct children.
